---
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import QuoteList from '../../components/QuoteList.astro';
import { TECHNIQUES } from '../../lib/techniques';

const t = TECHNIQUES.find((x) => x.slug === 'point-of-intention')!;
---

<Prose
  title={t.title}
  description={t.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Techniques', href: '/techniques/' }, { name: t.title }]}
  kicker="Technique"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: t.title }]}
>
  <p>
    The point of intention recovers the question a chart was cast for. It is used when a figure is
    found with no record of its question, or when a querent cannot say plainly what they have come
    to ask. The question normally comes first and makes the chart, so use this rule only when the
    question is genuinely missing or unclear.
  </p>

  <h2>Find the point of intention</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Count the single points, the odd lines, across the twelve house figures.</li>
    <li>Deal the count out one house at a time, the first, the second, the third, around the wheel, and keep going round until every point is placed.</li>
    <li>The house where the last point falls is the point of intention, the matter the figure was made for.</li>
    <li>Read that house and the figure standing in it for the likely class of question. The rule gives the house, not the exact wording.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>In the sources</h2>
  <p>
    Cattan gives the rules "for pleasure, and to shewe that Geomancie is a wittie Arte", with a
    second rule for reading the matter of another's thought:
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="intention" />
</Prose>
